<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Did any SNES games not use hioam?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12187&amp;p=138405#p138405"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Sik wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Wait, what's this discussion about overflowing? You're pretty much rewriting the entire table each time and sprites don't necessarily stay in the same entry in the OAM table, so the concept of modifying the X coordinate (as opposed to just overwriting it) doesn't make much sense, does it?<br /></div><br /><br />I agree. The idea of overflowing into the 9th bit/upper bit makes no sense. If you didn't want to worry about the High OAM table, you'll have to see if the sprite X calculated would wrap around and appear on the left and do something about it if that is not what you want to happen. That means either setting X in the High OAM table or setting Y to be off screen. But for sprites smoothly entering from the left you're going to have to use the X bit in High OAM. <br /><br />You just have to figure out your own reasonably efficient way to handle it. I recall psycopathicteen mentioning once that Gradius III wastes alot of time dealing with the High OAM. I forget the details of why.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1726">MottZilla</a> — Thu Jan 01, 2015 1:33 pm</p><hr />
